{
  "masechta": "Menachot",
  "daf": 69,
  "amud": "b",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "The Omer and Shtei HaLechem: Permitting New Grain in the Temple and in the Land",
      "display_title": "Omer & Shtei HaLechem",
      "timestamp": "00:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Introduction: The role of the Omer outside the Temple and Shtei HaLechem inside the Temple",
          "display_title": "Intro: Roles",
          "timestamp": "00:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Omer permits all grain, not just barley; misconceptions about grain types",
          "display_title": "Omer permits all grain",
          "timestamp": "00:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "Why Shtei HaLechem must be the first of new grain in the Temple; the status of Bikkurim",
          "display_title": "Shtei HaLechem & Bikkurim",
          "timestamp": "01:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "Mishnah: Prohibitions before the Omer are invalid; before Shtei HaLechem are valid",
          "display_title": "Mishnah: Kodem l'Omer",
          "timestamp": "01:37"
        },
        {
          "title": "Simple explanation: treif before Omer; only a custom before Shtei HaLechem",
          "display_title": "Simple explanation",
          "timestamp": "02:36"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rabbi Tarfon's Difficulty and Yehuda ben Nechemiah's Resolution",
      "display_title": "Tarfon & Yehuda",
      "timestamp": "03:21",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Tarfon's question: What is the difference between before the Omer and before Shtei HaLechem?",
          "display_title": "Tarfon's question",
          "timestamp": "03:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "Yehuda ben Nechemiah's answer: Before Omer it's treif; after Omer it becomes permissible to lay people",
          "display_title": "Yehuda's answer",
          "timestamp": "03:42"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Akiva's rebuke: Yehuda's arrogance toward the elder Tarfon",
          "display_title": "Akiva's rebuke",
          "timestamp": "04:48"
        },
        {
          "title": "The tragic conclusion: Yehuda ben Nechemiah dies young",
          "display_title": "Yehuda's death",
          "timestamp": "05:18"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Deeper Conceptual Issue: Single vs. Parallel Prohibitions",
      "display_title": "Deeper concept",
      "timestamp": "06:13",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Why Tarfon was troubled: The apparent obviousness of the answer",
          "display_title": "Tarfon's real issue",
          "timestamp": "06:13"
        },
        {
          "title": "Chiddushei HaRashba's explanation: Two models of prohibition",
          "display_title": "Rashba's models",
          "timestamp": "08:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Model One: Parallel prohibitions—one for lay people, one for the Temple",
          "display_title": "Model One: Parallel",
          "timestamp": "08:48"
        },
        {
          "title": "Model Two: Single prohibition extending from lay people to Temple, weakened after Omer",
          "display_title": "Model Two: Single",
          "timestamp": "09:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak on grapes: Testing the two models",
          "display_title": "Grapes test",
          "timestamp": "12:09"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Can the Omer and Shtei HaLechem Operate Out of Order?",
      "display_title": "Out of order?",
      "timestamp": "16:50",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rami bar Chama's question: Can Shtei HaLechem permit grain that encountered it before the Omer?",
          "display_title": "Rami's question",
          "timestamp": "16:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "The case: Grain planted between Omer and Shtei HaLechem",
          "display_title": "The case",
          "timestamp": "17:04"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's proof from a Braita about the Omer coming from barley",
          "display_title": "Rava's proof",
          "timestamp": "18:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Detailed examination: Three sources for why Omer comes from barley",
          "display_title": "Three sources",
          "timestamp": "19:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "The attempted resolution: Using grain from different crops",
          "display_title": "Different crops",
          "timestamp": "23:16"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's refutation: Focus on the Mizbeach, not the crops",
          "display_title": "Refutation",
          "timestamp": "25:35"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Stage of Plant Growth Required for Shtei HaLechem to Apply",
      "display_title": "Stage of growth",
      "timestamp": "27:53",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rami bar Chama's question: What stage (flowering or budding) does fruit need to reach?",
          "display_title": "Rami: growth stage",
          "timestamp": "27:53"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's discussion: Taking root vs. flowering of leaves",
          "display_title": "Taking root vs leaves",
          "timestamp": "28:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "Teiku: The question remains unresolved",
          "display_title": "Teiku",
          "timestamp": "30:20"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Status of Planted Seeds Before They Take Root",
      "display_title": "Planted seeds status",
      "timestamp": "31:38",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbah bar bar Channah's question: Seeds planted before Omer—does Omer permit them if they haven't taken root?",
          "display_title": "Rabbah: seeds in ground",
          "timestamp": "31:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "Are planted seeds like seeds in a vessel or already part of the ground?",
          "display_title": "Vessel analogy",
          "timestamp": "34:43"
        },
        {
          "title": "Three subsidiary questions: Ona'ah (overcharging), Shevu'ah (oaths), and the status of planted seeds",
          "display_title": "Three questions",
          "timestamp": "36:18"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ona'ah: Are overcharging laws applicable to planted seeds?",
          "display_title": "Ona'ah",
          "timestamp": "36:55"
        },
        {
          "title": "Shevu'ah: Can oaths be administered about planted seeds?",
          "display_title": "Shevu'ah",
          "timestamp": "41:35"
        },
        {
          "title": "All three questions left unresolved (Teiku)",
          "display_title": "All Teiku",
          "timestamp": "42:22"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Wheat Kernels from Animal Dung: Status as Food and for Korbanot",
      "display_title": "Dung & kernels",
      "timestamp": "42:51",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rami bar Chama's question: Status of wheat in cattle dung and barley in other animals",
          "display_title": "Rami: kernels status",
          "timestamp": "42:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "Braita: Intention alone doesn't make them food; extracting them does",
          "display_title": "Extracting matters",
          "timestamp": "44:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Can grain grown from dung-extracted kernels be used for Menachot?",
          "display_title": "Dung-grown grain",
          "timestamp": "45:19"
        },
        {
          "title": "Two theories: Disgustingness removed by planting, or weakness in potency (Teiku)",
          "display_title": "Two theories",
          "timestamp": "46:02"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Materials That Have Passed Through Animals: Digestion and Status Change",
      "display_title": "Digestion & status",
      "timestamp": "46:58",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rami bar Chama: Palm leaves swallowed by an elephant and excreted—what is their status?",
          "display_title": "Elephant & palm",
          "timestamp": "46:58"
        },
        {
          "title": "Are they now dung-vessels (cannot become tamei) or still palm-leaf vessels?",
          "display_title": "Dung vs palm",
          "timestamp": "47:44"
        },
        {
          "title": "Proof from Ulla: The wolves' story—flesh changed, bones did not",
          "display_title": "Wolves story",
          "timestamp": "51:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclusion: Flesh is soft (changes status), bones are hard (don't change)—palm leaves are intermediate (Teiku)",
          "display_title": "Intermediate status",
          "timestamp": "52:25"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tosafot's principle: If form hasn't changed, status should remain the same",
          "display_title": "Tosafot's principle",
          "timestamp": "54:39"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Can Grain Be Offered That Fell from the Clouds?",
      "display_title": "Grain from clouds",
      "timestamp": "55:14",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Zeira's question: If wheat rained from the sky, can it be used for Menachot?",
          "display_title": "Zeira: rain question",
          "timestamp": "55:14"
        },
        {
          "title": "Two interpretations of 'your dwellings': Anywhere not outside Israel, or specifically from your land",
          "display_title": "Two interpretations",
          "timestamp": "55:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Can such an event actually occur? A story of wheat raining on a nomad",
          "display_title": "It can happen",
          "timestamp": "56:57"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
